\begin_layout Subsubsection
Overview
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Three wind-sensing systems are described in this document: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

standard
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 wind sensing system that uses pressure ports on the radome combined with
 airspeed measured using a pitot tube and ground-speed measured by an inertial
 reference unit and a global positioning system (GPS) receiver.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A gust-pod system consisting of a Rosemount 858 airflow sensor mounted under
 the wing combined with an inertial system co-located with the airflow sensor
 and linked to GPS measurements via a Kalman filter.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A laser air motion sensor described by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SpulerEtAl2011"

\end_inset

 combined with another IRU/GPS system.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although the measurement components differ, for each of these the measurement
 of wind involves the vector sum of two components, the motion of the air
 relative to the aircraft and the motion of the aircraft relative to the
 Earth.
 The former is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

relative wind
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and is measured as a three-component vector having magnitude equal to the
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true airspeed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and angles relative to the aircraft reference frame characterized by the
 angle of attack and the sideslip angle.
 The angle of attack is considered positive if the relative wind is from
 below the aircraft, and the sideslip angle is considered positive if the
 relative wind is from the starboard side of the aircraft.
 The relative wind defined in the coordinate system of the aircraft (conventiona
lly with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x^{\prime}}$
\end_inset

 forward, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y^{\prime}}$
\end_inset

 in the starboard direction, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z^{\prime}}$
\end_inset

 obtained from the cross product 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x^{\prime}}\times\hat{y^{\prime}}$
\end_inset

 and so approximately downward but oriented to align with the aircraft reference
 frame) must be transformed to an Earth-based reference system (conventionally
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

 toward east, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}$
\end_inset

 toward north, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}$
\end_inset

 upward) so that the components can be combined to yield the Earth-relative
 wind.
 This transformation is a function of the attitude angles of the aircraft,
 heading (
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

), pitch (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

), and roll (
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

), measured by an inertial reference unit in all three cases discussed here.
 Once in an Earth-based reference system, the relative wind vector is added
 to the vector representing the aircraft motion relative to the Earth to
 obtain the wind.
 The sources of the various measurements entering this processing sequence
 vary among the three systems and will be discussed separately below for
 each system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Relative Wind
\begin_inset CommandInset label
